during the Wars of the Roses through Richard <i>Neville</i> (1428–71), 16th Earl of Warwick, nicknamed \"The Kingmaker\".","Irish (Munster): assimilation of the Gaelic name <b>Ó Niadh</b> (see   Nee  ) and sometimes of <b>Ó Cnaimhín</b> (see   Nevin  ).","History: George Neville came to VA in or <i>c.</i> 1700 and settled on the headwaters of the Occoquan River, acquiring a large estate. His descendants, bearing the surnames Neville and Craig, were of considerable importance in Pittsburgh, PA, and Cincinnati, OH."],"variants":[{"name":"Nevells","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Nevils","meanings":["English: variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Novel","meanings":["English: variant of   Neville  .","Catalan: variant of   Novell  ."]},{"name":"Newell","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Neville  .","English: variant of   Noel  .","English: variant of   Newhall  ."]},{"name":"Nevills","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Neville  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Nevil","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Newill","meanings":["English and Irish (or Norman origin): variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Nevill","meanings":["English and Irish: of Norman origin, a variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Nevels","meanings":["English and Scottish (Wigtownshire): of Norman origin, a variant of   Neville  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is now rare in Britain.","Dutch and North German: unexplained."]},{"name":"Nee","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Dermot, John Patrick.","Irish (Galway): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Niadh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Nia</i>’ or <b>Mac Niadh</b> ‘son of <i>Nia</i>’. Compare   McNee  .   Needham   2 and   Neville   have also been adopted as Anglicized forms of this name.","North German: possibly a relationship name from Middle Low German <i>neve</i> ‘nephew, grand-child’."]}]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant of   Dev ."],"variants":[{"name":"Deborah","meanings":["Biblical name (meaning ‘bee’ in Hebrew), borne by the nurse of Rebecca (Genesis 35:8) and by a woman judge and prophet (Judges 4–5) who led the Israelites to victory over the Canaanites. It has always been popular as a Jewish name. It was in use among Christians by the mid 16th century and was taken up by the Puritans in the 17th century, in part because the bee was a symbol of industriousness. Since then it has enjoyed enormous popularity, peaking in the 1960s. Among other famous bearers is the actress  Deborah Kerr  (  1921–2007 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":58,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Henry de Nevill